const faqItems = [
  { q: 'How often should I replace my pool skimmer net?', a: 'Based on our 6-month durability tests, most quality nets last 2-3 seasons with regular use. Nets showing frayed edges, UV damage, or reduced debris pickup should be replaced immediately.' },
  { q: 'What mesh size is best for pool skimmer nets?', a: 'For general debris (leaves, bugs, twigs), standard mesh works fine. For fine particles and pollen, look for fine mesh nets with 0.5mm openings or smaller.' },
  { q: 'Do expensive pool skimmer nets perform significantly better?', a: 'Our tests found diminishing returns above $45. The sweet spot is $15-45, where we saw the best durability-to-performance ratio.' },
  { q: 'Can pool skimmer nets handle large leaves?', a: 'Yes, but larger leaves require a wider-mouth skimmer (at least 10-inch opening). Small nets clog quickly with big debris.' },
  { q: 'How do I prevent my skimmer net from tearing?', a: 'Rinse after each use, avoid overfilling, store away from direct sunlight, and replace when you see fraying. UV exposure is the #1 cause of early failure.' },
